2500|$|Leonardo da Vinci, (1452–1519) {{may have}} been the first in Europe to {{recognize}} certain special <b>optical</b> <b>qualities</b> of the eye. He derived his insights partly through introspection but mainly through a process that could be described as optical modelling. Based on dissection of the human eye he made experiments with water-filled crystal balls. He wrote [...] "The function of the human eye, ... was described by a large number of authors in a certain way. But I found it to be completely different." ...|$|E
2500|$|Leonardo da Vinci (1452–1519) is {{believed}} to be the first to recognize the special <b>optical</b> <b>qualities</b> of the eye. He wrote [...] "The function of the human eye ... was described by a large number of authors in a certain way. But I found it to be completely different." [...] His main experimental finding was that there is only a distinct and clear vision at the line of sight—the optical line that ends at the fovea. Although he did not use these words literally he actually is the father of the modern distinction between foveal and peripheral vision.|$|E
